crops.description: A fine-flavored South African papaya, pollinized by a plant from the Sandwich Islands. Seeds presented.

crops.institution_involved: Institute of Paint and Varnish Research, Washington, D. C., through the Bureau of Chemistry and Soils
crops.description: Seeds collected by H. A. Gardner. A large tropical tree of the Brazilian forests, with rigid leathery oblong leaves 3 to 5 inches long and shining green above. The greenish, ovoid-cylindrical fruits, about 2 inches long, yield an oil known as Oiticica oil, that is used in the paint and varnish industry.

crops.presented_by: Arthur W. Burrows, American consular agent, Coquimbo
crops.description: Seeds purchased. A small papaya 3 1/2 by 4 1/2 inches, with very thin flesh which is highly acid and is used only in making preserves and sirups. The fruit is yellow when ripe with a spicy aromatic flavor and fragrance, but is never eaten fresh.

crops.description: Santa Maria. A new type of rice developed near Rio Pardo, State of Rio Grande do Sul, which develops abnormally large ears and is a heavy yielder. Seeds presented.

Seeds collected in the Jardim Botanico, Rio de Janeiro, by H. A. Gardner. For previous introduction and description see 106347.

Seeds collected by Mrs. Thomas Barbour on the road between Ressano Garcia and Lourenço Marques, Mozambique. The "sausage tree" of eastern tropical Africa becomes 30 to 50 feet high, with rough ternate leaves made up of seven to nine elliptic-oblong leaflets; the large claret-colored flowers are in long spikes, and the blunt sausagelike fruits are 12 to 18 inches long.

No. 2488. A tropical shrub with thick leathery oval-elliptic dark-green leaves and small white flowers in large terminal cymes. It is native to Brazil. For the introduction of plants see 106371. Introduced as seeds.

No. 2483. Garuru. A handsome tree with leathery elliptic leaves shining green above and 4 to 6 inches long and large yellow flowers. Native to sandy places in British Guiana. For the introduction of plants see 106372. Introduced as seeds.
No. 2493. A cultivated variety. Introduced as seeds.

No. 2490. Cuttings of a large tropical tree with opposite digitately 3- to 5-foliolate leathery leaves, large greenish flowers, and hard-shelled nuts with white edible kernels. Native to northern South America.
No. 2478. Cuttings from a small tree of rather straggly habit with golden-yellow flowers in loose racemes. For previous introduction see 97567.
No. 2491. A cultivated watermelon collected at Bartica, on the Essequiba River. Introduced as seeds.
No. 2449. Bulbs of cultivated plants collected at Mazaruni Station.
No. 2450. Bulbs of cultivated plants.
No. 2480. Kanakudiballi. Introduced as seeds.
